benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/bundles/{bundleId}/auditLogsWithHistory - Retrieve bundle audit logs with history by id

covered: Valid Request: TC01 verifies successful retrieval with status 200, content-type, schema and bundleId correlation.
Empty Response: TC02 covers the case where a bundle exists but has no audit logs (empty JSON array).
Not Found / Error Responses: TC03, TC15, TC16 cover 404 when bundle is not present; TC07 covers service-unavailable (503).
Authorization: TC05 and TC06 cover missing and invalid authentication (401).
Input Validation / Path Parameter Format: TC04, TC19, TC20 validate invalid UUIDs, whitespace and special characters in bundleId.
Security: TC11 covers SQL injection attempts and ensures no internal errors are exposed.
Performance / Large Dataset: TC10 addresses large result sets and response-time expectation; TC17 covers concurrent requests (load/concurrency).
Schema & Data Quality: TC01 explicitly checks response schema; TC13 covers regression for malformed audit log entries.
Robustness / Recoverability: TC12 covers retry after transient network failure.
Compatibility / Integration: TC14 checks consistency with other audit-log endpoints.
HTTP semantics: TC21 verifies method-not-allowed (405) for non-GET usage.
Endpoint variants / edge cases: TC08 (unexpected query params) and TC18 (trailing slash) are present.
gaps: Pagination: No explicit tests for pagination semantics (limit/offset/page parameters), page boundaries, or behavior when results exceed a single page. TC10 tests a large dataset performance but does not verify paged responses or pagination headers.
Caching Behavior / Conditional GETs: No tests for caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional requests (If-None-Match / 304).
Rate Limiting / Throttling semantics: TC17 stresses concurrency but there are no tests validating rate limits, throttling behavior or 429 responses.
Authorization granularity: Tests cover missing/invalid token (401) but not authorized-but-forbidden scenarios (403) where a valid user lacks permission to view the bundle.
Internal Server Error (500) handling: No test exercising server-side failures that should produce 500 and safe error messages.
Content Negotiation / Accept header: No tests for handling different Accept headers (e.g., application/xml) or malformed Accept values.
Query parameters positive/negative coverage: Apart from an unexpected param (TC08), there are no tests for supported query parameters (if any) or invalid combinations.
Rate / Performance thresholds: TC10 and TC17 assert response time/load qualitatively, but they lack measurable, repeatable performance assertions and resource/throughput metrics.
Input length / extreme path values: There is no test for excessively long bundleId strings (length limits) or URL-encoded values beyond whitespace/special chars.
recommendations: Add explicit pagination tests (if the API supports pagination): request with page/limit/offset, verify paging headers or structure, test page boundaries and last-page behavior.
Add caching/conditional GET tests: verify Cache-Control and ETag/Last-Modified headers, and conditional requests returning 304 Not Modified.
Add rate-limiting/throttling tests: flood the endpoint to provoke 429 responses and verify retry-after headers and graceful degradation.
Add a forbidden (403) test: authenticated user with insufficient permissions should receive 403 (distinct from 401).
Simulate server errors: add tests that force DB or service failures to verify 500 responses do not leak internals and contain user-friendly error messages.
Add content-negotiation tests: call the endpoint with different Accept headers (including invalid ones) to confirm proper behavior.
If any query parameters are supported, add positive and negative tests for them (valid values, invalid values, combination of params).
Strengthen performance tests: make TC10/TC17 measurable and repeatable with defined thresholds and monitoring (p95/p99 latency, throughput), and include cleanup/setup to avoid flakiness.
Add tests for extreme/invalid path lengths and URL-encoded bundleIds to ensure robust validation and avoid path parsing issues.
